english:
  title: Eulogy of Twelve Celestial Steeds
  author: Choi Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the seventh year of Chun-sun, spring, the king showed his twelve finest steeds—the very ones he had ridden before ascending the throne—to his servant, and spoke thus:

    "Since ancient times, those sovereigns who have seized the mandate of heaven have all mounted their steeds through peril and conflict, ranging across the four quarters to establish extraordinary deeds. Yet among all creatures that share one heart with man and rush forward to offer their strength, none compares to the horse. The Charger of Xiang Yu or the Redmane of Liu Bang—these are hardly worthy of note. Only Tang Taizong's Six Steeds and our Great Ancestor's Eight Steeds shine forth brilliantly across the centuries. I myself have long devoted myself to archery and horsemanship. Though I have not borne the burden of warfare, I remember well the flourishing reign of King Sejong, when each spring and autumn I rode forth with the royal procession, testing my archery against all comers. I ever took the lead, and none could match my courage. The Three Armies rang with wonder and admiration, competing to sing my praises beneath the sovereign's gaze—how many times did my service delight the royal countenance! My strength lay merely in mastering the untamable and riding the unrideable. Among these steeds, the Red One that flew like lightning at the crucible and target was unmatched in swiftness; the Dappled One that bore me through the realm's peril showed a cunning without equal. Moreover, since the very arts of archery and horsemanship have laid the foundation of our world's order today, how can we forget the faithful service of those steeds? Following the ancient precedent of Tang, I would paint and transmit their images to posterity as a lesson for our descendants. You shall inscribe the meaning of this work."

    Your servant observes that whenever ancient sovereigns have overcome adversity and established lasting dynasties, they have always had heroic champions who seized the winds of fortune to become their hearts and vessels of talent. Likewise, they have always possessed extraordinary and transcendent steeds whose powerful strides became their wings of victory. These are the workings of Heaven's great design, where exceptional beings await their destined hour. They are born by Heaven's decree, encounter their moment by Heaven's hand. This is not the work of men alone. If even these noble beasts are born and meet their destiny through Heaven, are they not kindred to men?

    Imagine these creatures: wind-swift hooves, lightning-bright eyes, scaling hillsides and crossing towns, responding left and right to the slightest touch of rein, now galloping swift, now stepping measured, understanding human will as if possessed of spirits—leaping over peril, evading danger. They would traverse the Tan Valley without stumbling, cross the Dark Waters as if dry land. Upon these noble backs rests the weight of a hundred years of life; through them are built ten thousand generations of glory. When we measure their strength and strength of sinew, when we recount their deeds of running and leaping, surely they merit place among the martial heroes of old. How can we hold them in low regard?

    Reverently I consider: Our Sagely Ancestor, endowed by Heaven with courage and wisdom, commanded all the realm's heroes, and mounted beneath him rode eight celestial steeds—already exceeding Tang's count. Our present Majesty, bearing the celestial gift of holiness and continuing his forebear's sacred legacy, commands steeds numbering twelve—surpassing even that glorious predecessor. Rare indeed are such exceptional beings, yet rarer still is the opportunity to gather them. Yet when opportunity meets worthiness, even the heavenly stables do not withhold their treasures, nor do the spirit-mountains begrudge their offspring. These twelve steeds have come forth together—surely this is no accident, but Heaven's blessing!

    When the divinely-martial sage arose, the celestial steeds came naturally in his train. Through them the realm's evil was swept away and great calamity subdued as water poured downhill. The lands grew pure and the cosmos was remade. Though Heaven has ever guarded sacred warfare, it was upon these very steeds that the victory was achieved. Is this not the very working of destiny—where great purpose finds its instrument and exceptional talent meets its hour?

    Compare this to Zhou's Eight Steeds or Han's Nine Excellent, which served no grand purpose but merely ran in vain—how far inferior! The Sovereign has already inscribed the deeds of his ministers upon the Kirin Pavilion, and now remembers his faithful mounts, capturing them in paint that their traces endure timeless and their names descend through ages. Such is the compassion shown even to beasts—how much more shall it extend to men! Surely exceptional talents shall flock to the royal gaze in ever-greater numbers. Let descendants remember well the Sovereign's purpose in creating these images, comparing them to the River Map's eternal teachings, transmitting them unchanging through the ages. Then shall our Eastern realm's ten thousand generations of great royal achievement forever flourish through this very art.

    Bold and reverent, I affix these praises:

    **The Dappled Steed of Order:** A sage rising to meet destiny's call—all creatures receive heaven's blessing. One clash of will and heaven and earth grow clear and still.

    **The Scarlet Mist Galloper:** Rosy mist flows swift on wind—the crimson blood still gleams. Through reeds and crucibles his arrows sang, miraculous beyond measure.

    **The Pear-White Mare:** A light as clouds scattered through the Milky Way, petals scattered by wind. Arrow-flights make soundless strikes; one touch of rein and he cuts across the path.

    **The Jade-Bright Dragon-Steed:** Rising through clouded peaks with mighty bounds, touching empty air—a thousand leagues in a day, sometimes bearing a dragon-sage astride.

    **The Cloud-Piercing Crane:** Bearing the essence of the celestial horses, with the bearing of clouds' white crane. When the lord hunts, the multitudes marvel at his subtle mastery.

    **The Wind-Chasing Colt:** Born swift as heaven itself—swifter than wind itself! Though arrows rest in precious sheath, his name towers higher than mountains.

    **The Arrow-Cloud Dragon:** Dragon-form in verdant hue, hooves strike at cloudbanks blue. Dragon-descended, unmatched in height and speed.

    **The Mist-Riding Leopard:** Red leopard flying through darkness—bounding across stone, none match his fearsome power.

    **The Swift-Soaring Pheasant:** Red eagle breasting the wind—crimson pearls shot through the void. Morning in Yan, evening in Yue, his shadow swifter than startled cranes.

    **The Dragon-Winged Steed:** More noble than the Flying Yellow, more miraculous than the White. Like children of the River Han, bearing divine dragon-wings.

    **The Crowned Unicorn:** Spiritual essence drawn from moonlight, excellence gathered from the stars. Mane streaming across vast reaches—no steed remains in northern Chi.

    **The Night-Bright Charger:** Frost-light illuminates darkness, rainbow-radiance brightens heaven. Swift as wings, swift as flight—what distance lies beyond his reach?
  footnotes:
    - The Six Steeds of Tang Taizong and the Eight Steeds of the Joseon founder are legendary in East Asian equestrian lore, representing the perfect union of ruler and mount in establishing dynasties.
    - The references to Xiang Yu's Charger and Liu Bang's Redmane, while famous in Chinese history, serve as foils—their masters' achievements fell short of these steeds' potential.
    - The imagery of wind and lightning, coupled with spiritual perceptiveness, reflects the Neo-Confucian view that exceptional beings embody cosmic principles.
    - The River Map (河圖) is a legendary cosmological diagram symbolizing eternal cosmic order—comparing the sovereign's paintings to this elevates them as instruments of lasting governance.
    - The 'Eight Dragons' and 'Nine Excellent' of Zhou and Han represent historical precedents that the Joseon dynasty surpasses, asserting Korea's position as the true heir to celestial mandate.
